 No, malloc does not initialize allocated memory to zero. When you call malloc, it allocates the requested amount of memory, but that memory contains whatever values were previously stored in that location (essentially garbage values).

If you need memory initialized to zero, you should use calloc instead, which automatically initializes all allocated memory to zero. Alternatively, you can use malloc followed by memset to manually set the memory to zero or another value.

For example:
```c
// Using malloc (memory not initialized)
int *array = (int *)malloc(10 * sizeof(int));
// array now contains random/garbage values

// Using calloc (memory initialized to zero)
int *zeroed_array = (int *)calloc(10, sizeof(int));
// zeroed_array contains all zeros

// Using malloc + memset
int *another_array = (int *)malloc(10 * sizeof(int));
memset(another_array, 0, 10 * sizeof(int));
// another_array now contains all zeros
```

